# Planner — bowling-shirt-designer

Build plan for a full (richness 10) 3D bowling-shirt e-commerce customizer that
doubles as proof of the exact skills the posting audits: state-management rigor
(no dead clicks / `undefined is not an object`) and homepage load performance.

## Stack decision (revisits intake — honor Michael's explicit ask)

Michael said explicitly: "Use next JS and let's do a true php backend routed
through my python backend." Intake downgraded both to Vite + narrative-only PHP.
Planner overrides toward Michael's stated intent where it survives the static
same-origin hosting model:

- **Frontend: Next.js 14 (App Router) with `output: 'export'`**, `basePath` +
  `assetPrefix` = `/demos/bowling-shirt-designer`, `images.unoptimized: true`.
  Static export drops into `../michaelwegter.com/public/demos/bowling-shirt-designer/`
  exactly like a Vite build — same zero-friction GH Pages deploy, but honors the
  Next.js requirement and lets the proposal truthfully say "Next.js." Keep demo
  source in `upwork-runs/bowling-shirt-designer/demo-src/`.
- **3D: Three.js + @react-three/fiber + @react-three/drei**. Canvas is a
  client-only component, dynamically imported (`next/dynamic`, `ssr:false`) so it
  is code-split and NOT in the homepage critical path — this is the literal fix
  for the client's "heavy script blocking / instant bounce" problem and we make
  that visible (fast first paint, canvas lazy-mounts on view/interaction).
- **State: Zustand** single store (customizer + cart). Deliberately chosen and
  called out as the antidote to the client's `undefined is not an object` /
  dead-click failures (no unguarded nested reads, selectors, immer-safe updates).
- **Styling: Tailwind + CSS vars** for the retro palette. Fonts via
  next/font (Google): Bebas Neue (display), Inter (UI).
- **Backend: real PHP microservice proxied through Flask** — CONFIRMED feasible
  (Q5). Tiny PHP built-in-server app (`php -S 127.0.0.1:5060`) with 3 endpoints
  (`GET /patterns`, `POST /session`, `GET /session/<id>`, flat-file JSON storage,
  no MySQL). Registered as a Surface service (`bowling-php`, port 5060) so it
  stays up across reboots. Flask blueprint `bowling_blueprint.py` (clone the
  bridge template, PREFIX=`/bowling`, UPSTREAM=`http://127.0.0.1:5060`) proxies
  `/bowling/*` and is the sole public origin. This makes "true PHP routed through
  Python" real, not narrative. **Single gatekeeper:** demo-builder step 1 runs
  `php --version` on the Surface; if winget/PHP is unavailable in the runner user
  context, fall back cleanly to a Flask-only blueprint with the same endpoints and
  describe PHP in the proposal architecture diagram. Record the outcome in
  build-report.md. PHP source is written to disk as a file (runner scripts stay
  ASCII-only per playbook), not embedded inline.

## Features (all fully working)

### HERO — 3D Interactive Customizer
- Orbit controls (rotate/zoom/pan), auto-rotate idle, reset-view button.
- Shirt model: **procedural mesh** (Q1 decided — no reliable free bowling GLTF).
  4 groups: ShirtBody (Box + shoulder spheres, material #0), Collar (Torus, #1),
  Sleeves (x2 Cylinders, #2), BackPanel (child PlaneGeometry, z-offset +0.101,
  flat 0→1 UV = zero-distortion text surface). 3 named material indices drive
  per-segment color.
- Pattern library: **6 canvas-generated tileable patterns** (Q2 — Atomic
  Starburst, Bowling Pins, Argyle Diamond, 50s Polka Dot, Lane Chevrons, Atomic
  Bowtie), drawn to 512x512 at module init → `THREE.CanvasTexture`,
  `wrapS=wrapT=RepeatWrapping`, `repeat.set(3,3)`. Zero network/license risk. Plus
  **live user upload** (PNG/SVG) → `URL.createObjectURL` → THREE.Texture applied
  instantly as repeating map.
- Per-segment color pickers: base body, collar, cuffs/trim independent materials
  (each `<meshStandardMaterial color={store.*}>`, re-renders on store change).
- Text-on-back: font + color + size + text input → offscreen 512x256 canvas →
  `THREE.CanvasTexture` → drei `<Decal position={[0,0.1,-0.101]} rotation={[0,PI,0]}
  scale={[0.5,0.25,1]}>` on the back face (Q7 — Decal is the r3f-idiomatic choice;
  BackPanel `.material.map` is the equally-valid simpler fallback). Visible when
  rotated to back. Debounce input 150ms to avoid per-keystroke texture rebuild.
- Save/share: POST customization to backend, returns id; GET rehydrates it.

### SUPPORTING 1 — Product Page + Cart
- Size selector (S/M/L/XL/2XL), quantity, price, Add to Cart.
- Cart persisted in localStorage; each line item shows a **customization
  thumbnail** captured from the canvas (renderer.domElement.toDataURL at add).
- Cart drawer with edit/remove, subtotal. No payment/checkout (scope fence).

### SUPPORTING 2 — Audit Credibility Section
- On-page section that answers the posting directly: a side-by-side "Before
  (the failure pattern) vs After (this build's architecture)" table —
  dead-click / `undefined is not an object` root cause vs guarded state; heavy
  synchronous script vs code-split lazy canvas; plus a one-screen
  "Technical Remediation Roadmap" mirroring the deliverable the client asked for.
- Ties the demo explicitly to Microsoft Clarity findings.

## Production-quality requirements (richness 10)
- Error boundary around the Canvas (graceful fallback, never a white-screen).
- Loading skeleton + Suspense on first paint; homepage interactive before 3D loads.
- Mobile responsive: canvas → portrait, controls stack below.
- Zero console errors on first paint (hard gate).
- Subtle entrance transitions (CSS only, no heavy animation lib).
- a11y: labelled controls, keyboard-usable pattern/color pickers.

## Scope fences
1 shirt model. Customizer → product page → cart only (no checkout/payment).
PNG/SVG uploads only. 5 preset sizes. ~12 files for demo touch budget. 1 hero +
2 supporting features, nothing more. 3-min build timeout. PHP realness gated on
Q5 — do NOT sink unbounded time into Surface PHP; fall back cleanly.

## Design direction (bespoke, zero michaelwegter.com tokens)
Retro-modern bowling alley — 1960s Americana meets clean SaaS.
- Palette (CONFIRMED accurate vs Hammer/Ebonite/Brunswick, Q3): navy `#1a1f3c`,
  cream `#f5f0e8`, coral `#e84040`, gold `#f5a623`, white `#ffffff`.
- Type: Bebas Neue (display/hero), Inter (body/UI).
- Layout (Custom Ink / RushOrderTees configurator pattern, Q3): canvas center-left
  ~60% with visible orbit controls; options panel right sidebar ~35% (color
  pickers as clickable swatch circles, pattern picker, text tool stacked);
  Front/Back toggle button above canvas (rotates camera, not swap mesh); Add to
  Cart CTA pinned at sidebar bottom. Mobile: canvas full-width top, options scroll
  below. Bowling-alley motifs (chevrons, lane arrows, pin/ball) as SVG accents.

